AI art only started in 2014, and then it could only generate galleries of semi-lifelike human faces. It has gotten a lot better, very quickly. I would not be surprised if it learns how to do hands and non-mutated faces reliably. Someone who has a tool like Stable Diffusion and the art skills I lack could probably use SD to grind out a few hundred images at a time (with sufficiently studly hardware it will take less time to generate them than it takes to look over them in the next step), pick out a few that look most promising, and photoshop them into something passing decent--if he knows how to draw hands himself. The process, overall, would surely be vastly faster than starting with from nothing. Rumor has it some freelance artists are already doing this. I don't know how to feel about this.
